05986nam a22009255i 9780823264407DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20152015nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808232644077 a10.1515/97808232644072doi  a(DE-B1597)555122  a(OCoLC)914229950  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aB105.L54b.T47 2015eb 7aPHI0010002bisacsh04a128/.422300aThresholds of Listening :bSound, Technics, Space /ced. by Sander van Maas. 1aNew York, NY : bFordham University Press, c[2015] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (324 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tIntroduction -- t1. The Auditory Re-Turn (The Point of Listening) -- t2. “Dear Listener . . .”: Music and the Invention of Subjectivity -- t3. Scenes of Devastation: Interpellation, Finite and Infi nite -- t4. Positive Feedback: Listening behind Hearing -- t5. “Antennas Have Long Since Invaded Our Brains” -- t6. Movement at the Boundaries of Listening, Composition, and Performance -- t7. The Biopolitics of Noise: Kafka’s “Der Bau” -- t8. Torture as an Instrument of Music -- t9. Stop It, I Like It! -- t10. Sounds of Belonging -- t11. Back to the Beat -- t12. The Discovery of Slowness in Music -- t13. Negotiating Ecstasy -- tNOTES -- tCONTRIBUTORS -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThresholds of Listening addresses recent and historical changes in the ways listening has been conceived. Listening, having been emancipated from the passive, subjected position of reception, has come to be asserted as an active force in culture and in collective and individual politics.The contributors to this volume show that the exteriorization of listening— brought into relief by recent historical studies of technologies of listening—involves a re-negotiation of the theoretical and pragmatic distinctions that underpin the notion of listening. Focusing on the manifold borderlines between listening and its erstwhile others, such as speaking, reading, touching, seeing, or hearing, the book maps new frontiers in the history of aurality. They suggest that listening’s finitude— defined in some of the essays as its death or deadliness—should be considered as a heuristic instrument rather than as a mere descriptor.Listening emerges where it appears to end or to run up against thresholds and limits—or when it takes unexpected turns. Listening’s recent emergence on the cultural and theoretical scene may therefore be productively read against contemporary recurrences of the motifs of elusiveness, finitude, and resistance to open up new politics, discourses, and technologies of aurality.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aListening (Philosophy). 4aCinema & Media Studies. 4aMusic. 4aPhilosophy & Theory. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Aesthetics.2bisacsh  aaddress.  aaurality'.  ahearing technology.  aliminal.  alistening.  asenses.  atropes.1 aAdler, Anthony Curtis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFreeman, Jason, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHamilton, John T., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKramer, Lawrence, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKromhout, Melle Jan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMaas, Sander van, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPlate, Liedeke, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRehding, Alexander, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aShenton, Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSholl, Robert, econtributor.